related_questions.question: Is sausage healthy yes or no?
related_questions.snippet: Eating too much bacon, sausages, hot dogs, canned meat, or lunch meat—meat that has been processed in some way to preserve or flavor it—is bad for health, according to experts. A number of studies have found links between processed meat and various forms of cancer, as well as heart disease and diabetes.

related_questions.question: What is sausage made of?
related_questions.snippet: Sausages can be made by grinding meat from beef, pork, poultry, or game meat, mixing with salt and other seasonings followed by stuffing into a container or a casing. The word sausage is derived from the Latin word salsus, which means salted or preserved by salting.
related_questions.title: Basics of Sausage Making; Formulation, Processing & Safety

related_questions.question: Why is it called sausage?
related_questions.snippet: The word sausage, from the Latin salsus (“salted”), refers to a food-processing method that had been used for centuries. Various forms of sausages were known in ancient Babylonia, Greece, and Rome, and early North American Indians made pemmican, a compressed dried meat-and-berry cake.

buttons.subtitle: Origin Of Sausage
buttons.title: Sausage - Wikipedia
buttons.snippet: Etymology. The word sausage was first used in English in the mid-15th century, spelled sawsyge. This word came from Old North French saussiche (Modern French saucisse). The French word came from Vulgar Latin salsica ("sausage"), from salsicus ("seasoned with salt").
